---

<Chapter title="What is a Token?">
  <Heading>How we communicate with Redis?</Heading>

  <Prose>
    <strong>Redis</strong> follows a traditional <strong
      >Client-Server architecture.</strong
    > One or many Redis Clients send commands like <Keyword word="GET" />, <Keyword
      word="SET"
    />, or <Keyword word="DEL" /> to a single central <strong
      >Redis Server.</strong
    > The server reads the command from the connection, <strong>parses</strong> it,
    <strong>evaluates</strong>
    it, and <strong>writes</strong> the response back to the client.

    <p>
      But how does the server actually <strong>understand a command</strong>? To
      a computer, <Keyword word="SET userName Alejandro" /> is nothing more than
      a raw string of characters. Before the <strong>server</strong> can act on it,
      it needs to transform it into a <strong>meaningful representation.</strong
      >
      That process is called <Keyword word="Parsing" />.
    </p>

    <p>
      So, before we can evaluate a Command, we are going to transform it twice
      into more accessible representations:
    </p>

    <Picture
      class="w-full my-40"
      loading="eager"
      src="/articles/commands-transformations.svg"
      alt="Commands transformations"
      size={514}
    />

    <p>
      The first transformation is turning our <strong>Raw Command</strong> into <Keyword
        word="Tokens"
      />, which are the <strong>atomic units</strong> that compose a Command Representation.

      <br />
      The process of turning raw text into meaningful Tokens is called <strong
        >Lexical Analysis</strong
      >, and it's done by a <Keyword word="Lexer" />.
    </p>

    <p>For example, feeding this command to our <Keyword word="Lexer" />:</p>

    <SETExample />

    <p>The <Keyword word="Lexer" /> Produces the following:</p>

    <SETTokens />

    <p>
      Notice that not all <Keyword word="Tokens" /> are equal. <Keyword
        word="SET"
      /> is a command token — it represents the <strong
        >operation to perform.</strong
      > The remaining two are <strong>identifier tokens</strong> — they carry the
      arguments. Each
      <Keyword word="Token" /> knows both what <strong>kind</strong> it is and what
      it <strong>contains</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>This is the theory — let's define some tokens!</p>

    <h3 class="fraunces">Defining Tokens</h3>

    <Picture
      src="/articles/token-example.svg"
      alt="Command tokens"
      size={1024}
    />

    <p>
      As shown above, <Keyword word="SET userName Alejandro" /> is not treated as
      one long string. The Lexer identifies three distinct Tokens: a <strong
        >command token</strong
      >
      and two <strong>identifier tokens</strong> — each with its own <Keyword
        word="TokenKind"
      />.
    </p>

    <p>
      <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> is the first entity we will define in our project.
      Enough theory — it's time to write our first lines of code.
    </p>

    <h3 class="fraunces my-20">Defining TokenKinds</h3>

    <Tokens />

    <p>
      As you can see, the first <Keyword word="TokenKinds" /> we define are <Keyword
        word="EOF"
      /> and <Keyword word="ILLEGAL" />. These two play very specific <strong
        >roles</strong
      > in our <Keyword word="Lexer" />:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="EOF" />: Stands for <strong>End Of File</strong> and signals
        that there is no more input to read.
      </li>
      <li>
        <Keyword word="ILLEGAL" />: represents any character our Lexer doesn't
        recognize.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <strong>
      Why use a <Keyword word="byte" /> for <Keyword word="TokenKind" />?
    </strong>

    <p>
      You might have noticed that we defined <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> as a <Keyword
        word="byte"
      />. This is a deliberate <strong>engineering decision</strong> — here's why
      we chose it over a <Keyword word="string" /> or a standard <Keyword
        word="int"
      />:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Memory Efficiency:</strong> Since our Lexer will generate a new instance
        for every single word or symbol in a command, using a <strong
          >1-byte</strong
        > type keeps our memory footprint as small as possible.
      </li>

      <li>
        <strong>Sufficient Capacity:</strong> A <Keyword word="byte" /> ( an alias
        for <Keyword word="uint8" /> ) can represent up to 256 unique values. Since
        our Redis clone will only have a few dozen command types and symbols, this
        is the perfect, lightweight fit for our <Keyword word="TokenKind" />.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      With our <Keyword word="TokenKind" /> defined, we now need a container to hold
      two things: the <strong>kind of token</strong> it is, and the <strong
        >raw text</strong
      > it was derived from — which as seen in the <strong
        >SET Tokens example</strong
      > we'll call the <Keyword word="Literal" />.
    </p>

    <TokenStruct />

    <p>
      🔥 <strong>Fun Fact:</strong> Even thought i just said that the <Keyword
        word="Token"
      /> struct should be as lightweight as possible, this is not the <strong
        >most lightweight representation</strong
      > for a Token.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <strong>Golang Parser</strong> uses an amazing technique: instead of storing
      a piece of text in the struct as we do, they just store the <strong
        >indices</strong
      > from where the piece of text beings and ends, a simple and ingenious trick
      if you want to implement it, <ExternalLink
        href="https://github.com/golang/go/blob/3fd729b2a14a7efcf08465cbea60a74da5457f06/src/go/token/position.go#L83"
        text="Check the details here"
      />.
    </p>

    <p>
      Now the only thing left is creating a constructor for our <Keyword
        word="Token"
      /> struct. This will make instantiating new Tokens clean and consistent throughout
      the codebase:
    </p>

    <TokenNew />
  </Prose>

  <TokensExercise />

  <Prose>
    <p>
      In the next chapter, we will build the <Keyword word="Lexer" /> — the engine
      responsible for turning a raw <strong>Redis command</strong> into exactly these
      <strong>tokens</strong>.
    </p>
  </Prose>

  <LinkContainer prevSection="requirements" nextSection="lexer" />
</Chapter>
